- Growth over time with cystic components and enhancing soft tissue and septations.  

B) Candidate pass/fail:  
1) Extragonadal germ cell tumour  
   - Pros: Occurs in midline/pelvic locations, can necrotic/cystic with enhancement.  
   - Cons: Typically solid mass, less likely to present as fat attenuation lesion; no mention of tumor markers or typical features; location is lateral ischiorectal fossa rather than midline; fat attenuation is unusual.  

2) Ischiorectal liposarcoma  
   - Pros: Fat containing mass in ischiorectal fossa; can enlarge and develop cystic/necrotic areas with irregular enhancement; often encapsulated.  
   - Cons: Usually heterogeneous from the start due to fat and soft tissue components; initial CT showed thin capsule without enhancement; cystic compartments and irregular enhancing rims are consistent with necrosis seen in liposarcoma.  

