   - Pros: Fat attenuation mass with possible cystic components; can have fat-fluid levels and calcifications; typically benign.  
   - Cons: Usually contains fat and calcifications; no calcifications noted here; location less common; growth with solid enhancing rims and septations less characteristic; dermoid cysts generally stable without significant growth or solid enhancement.  

4) Tailgut cyst (retrorectal cystic hamartoma)  
   - Pros: Location in presacral or ischiorectal fossa; cystic multiloculated lesion with fluid and enhancing septations; can enlarge over time; typical features on MRI include multiloculated cysts with varying signal intensities; irregular thick enhancing rim if infected or inflamed.  
   - Cons: Usually located presacral (midline), but can be eccentric; no mention of infection; fat attenuation less typical but possible due to proteinaceous content; but overall fits cystic nature with enhancing septa and rind.  

