A) Key findings:  
- Patient is a 9-year-old female with fever and restricted neck movements.  
- Clinical exam: posterior bulging of the mucosa in the posterior oropharyngeal/hypopharyngeal wall lateralized to the left; no piriform sinus irregularities.  
- CT neck: well-defined oval fluid collection with rim enhancement in the retropharyngeal space (2 x 2 x 1 cm).  
- Retropharyngeal space edema extends from skull base to hypopharynx.  
- Thin well-defined rim-enhancing fistulous tract from inferior left border of retropharyngeal collection to upper pole of left thyroid lobe.  

B) Candidate pass/fail with pros/cons:  
1) Retropharyngeal abscess  
- Pros: Fluid collection with rim enhancement in retropharyngeal space; clinical signs include fever, neck restriction, bulging of posterior oropharyngeal wall; edema extending through retropharyngeal space is typical.  
- Cons: Fistulous tract to thyroid gland is not typical. Usually abscess does not have fistulous tract to thyroid lobe.  
2) Atypically located third or fourth infected branchial cleft cyst  
- Pros: Branchial cleft cysts can be cystic lesions with possible infection leading to rim enhancement; fistulous tracts can be present in branchial cleft anomalies.  
- Cons: Location is somewhat atypical: retropharyngeal space is unusual for third/fourth branchial cleft cysts; also bulging mucosa lateralized to left oropharyngeal wall is not classic. Fistulous tract to thyroid is more typical of fourth branchial cleft cysts, but these are usually lateral neck, not retropharyngeal.  
3) Necrotic retropharyngeal adenopathy  
- Pros: Necrotic lymph nodes can appear as rim-enhancing fluid collections in retropharyngeal space.  
- Cons: Usually associated with underlying infection/neoplasm; no mention of primary source; fistulous tract to thyroid is not typical; also clinical findings of fistula and bulging mucosa are less compatible.  
4) Suppurative thyroiditis  
- Pros: Fistulous tract to thyroid pole; abscess formation in thyroid; swelling can track backward to retropharyngeal space.  
