 Tc-99m MIBI)
 
 was performed and an adenoma of the right inferior parathyroid was confirmed (Figures 5a and 5b).","Clinical History: A 53-year-old male patient presented with a lump in his left jaw, with noted enlargement in 2 months. There were no associated symptoms or relevant clinical history. Physical examination disclosed an expansile lesion in the left mandibular region and excluded palpable lymph nodes.
 Imaging Findings: Non-enhanced computed tomography (CT) dental scan showed an expansile lytic lesion centred to the angle and ascending ramus of the left mandible, measuring 4 cm at its largest axis, with well-defined, multilobulated borders and ground-glass ossified matrix. The final report included osteosarcoma and chondrosarcoma as diagnostic hypotheses and the patient was referred to our tertiary hospital. Contrast-enhanced cervical CT performed at our hospital better depicted that the lesion did not invade adjacent structures and enabled evaluation of the infra-hyoid neck. A solid, hypodense, 3.5 cm mass was identified posterior to the right thyroid lobe and a provisional diagnosis of parathyroid adenoma was proposed. On ultrasound, the referred nodule was well-defined and hypoechoic. Laboratory findings revealed elevated parathyroid hormone (PTH) (301pg/mL) and elevated calcium levels (13mg/dL). Parathyroid scintigraphy with technetium-99m methoxy-isobutyl-isonitrile (Tc-99m MIBI) was performed and an adenoma of the right inferior parathyroid was confirmed.","Giant cell tumour, Giant cell reparative granuloma, Fibrous dysplasia, Brown tumour, Ossifying fibroma",Brown tumour,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>  
A) Key findings:  
- Patient: 53-year-old male with a 4 cm expansile lytic lesion in the left mandible (angle and ascending ramus), well-defined multilobulated borders, ground-glass ossified matrix on CT.  
- No invasion of adjacent structures.  
- Physical exam: expansile lesion, no palpable lymph nodes.  
- Lab: elevated PTH (301 pg/mL) and hypercalcemia (13 mg/dL).  
- Imaging: contralateral (right) parathyroid adenoma confirmed by Tc-99m MIBI scintigraphy.  
- Initial diagnostic hypotheses included osteosarcoma and chondrosarcoma, but no invasive features were seen.  
- Ground-glass matrix and expansile lytic nature of the jaw lesion suggest fibro-osseous lesion rather than aggressive malignancy.  
- Presence of parathyroid adenoma suggests secondary bone changes secondary to hyperparathyroidism (brown tumor).  

B) Candidate pass/fail:  
1) Giant cell tumour:  
   - Pros: Commonly lytic with expansile nature; can affect the mandible.  
   - Cons: Usually does not present with ground-glass matrix; no hyperparathyroidism association; no typical multilobulated ground-glass matrix.  

2) Giant cell reparative granuloma:  
   - Pros: Can be expansile, lytic, with multilobulated borders.  
   - Cons: Rarely shows ground-glass matrix; not typically associated with hyperparathyroidism.  

3) Fibrous dysplasia:  
   - Pros: Ground-glass matrix is classic; well-defined expansile lesion in mandible; common in this region.  
   - Cons: Usually not associated with hyperparathyroidism; typically unilateral and stable; no evidence of hypermetabolic parathyroid adenoma.  

4) Brown tumour:  
   - Pros: Associated with hyperparathyroidism (elevated PTH, hypercalcemia); mimics expansile lytic bone lesions with ground-glass appearance; common in mandible; parathyroid adenoma found on contralateral side consistent with primary hyperparathyroidism; brown tumors are fibro-osseous lesions.  
   - Cons: Histopathology required to differentiate from other giant cell lesions; imaging can mimic other diseases but hyperparathyroidism strongly supports brown tumor.  

5) Ossifying fibroma:  
   - Pros: Expansile lesion with mixed lytic and sclerotic appearance possible; can have ground-glass matrix; typically well-circumscribed.  
   - Cons: Usually not associated with hyperparathyroidism; clinical and lab findings not typical; less common in this age group.  

C) Ranking with tie-breaks:  
1) Brown tumour - Strongly supported by clinical (hyperparathyroidism), lab (elevated PTH, hypercalcemia), and imaging (ground-glass matrix, expansile lytic lesion) findings.  
2) Fibrous dysplasia - Ground-glass matrix and lesion location fit; however, no hyperparathyroidism.  
3) Ossifying fibroma - Similar imaging appearance but no endocrine abnormalities.  
4) Giant cell tumour - Expansile lytic lesion fits, but no hyperparathyroidism.  
5) Giant cell reparative granuloma - Less likely due to lack of endocrine abnormalities and typical imaging features.  

Conclusion: With hyperparathyroidism confirmed and imaging features, the most consistent diagnosis is brown tumour, a manifestation of primary hyperparathyroidism-associated bone changes.  
</analysis>  
