18892,"Clinical History: A 13-year-old boy presented with pain over the left hip for the last 3 years and a gradually enlarging mass for the last 2 years. Upon physical examination, the left hip range of motion was reduced. Lab tests showed normal calcium, high serum phosphorous of 7.07 Eq/dL, and normal parathormone levels.
 Imaging Findings: A radiograph of the left hip demonstrated multilobulated periarticular calcifications (Figure 1). MRI (Figures 3a, 3b, 3c, 3d, and 3e) showed a well-defined, lobulated lesion affecting the glutei, vastus lateralis, and obturator externus muscles. Multiple fluid-calcium levels, termed the “sedimentation sign”, were noted, with calcifications appearing hypointense on both T1 and T2-weighted sequences, and fluid appearing hypointense on T1-weighted and hyperintense on T2-weighted sequences. These lesions exhibited heterogeneous contrast enhancement. CT imaging revealed a multilobulated calcific mass without bone or joint involvement (Figures 2a and 2b).
 
 Histopathological examination (Figures 4a and 4b) confirmed the diagnosis of tumoral calcinosis, revealing fibro-collagenous tissue with granular calcifications arranged in lobules with surrounding multinucleated giant cells, foamy macrophages, lymphocytes, and plasma cells.","Clinical History: A 13-year-old boy presented with pain over the left hip for the last 3 years and a gradually enlarging mass for the last 2 years. Upon physical examination, the left hip range of motion was reduced. Lab tests showed normal calcium, high serum phosphorous of 7.07 Eq/dL, and normal parathormone levels.
 Imaging Findings: A radiograph of the left hip demonstrated multilobulated periarticular calcifications. MRI showed a well-defined, lobulated lesion affecting the glutei, vastus lateralis, and obturator externus muscles. Multiple fluid-calcium levels, termed the “sedimentation sign”, were noted, with calcifications appearing hypointense on both T1 and T2-weighted sequences, and fluid appearing hypointense on T1-weighted and hyperintense on T2-weighted sequences. These lesions exhibited heterogeneous contrast enhancement. CT imaging revealed a multilobulated calcific mass without bone or joint involvement. Histopathological examination confirmed the diagnosis of tumoral calcinosis, revealing fibro-collagenous tissue with granular calcifications arranged in lobules with surrounding multinucleated giant cells, foamy macrophages, lymphocytes, and plasma cells.","Soft tissue sarcoma, Myositis ossificans, CPPD disease, Hydroxyapatite deposition disease, Hyperparathyroidism, Primary hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis, Synovial osteochrondromatosis",Primary hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>  
A) Key findings:  
- 13-year-old boy with chronic left hip pain (3 years) and gradually enlarging soft tissue mass (2 years).  
- Reduced hip range of motion.  
- Laboratory: normal calcium, elevated serum phosphorus (7.07 Eq/dL), normal PTH.  
- Imaging:  
  - Radiograph: multilobulated periarticular calcifications around the left hip.  
  - MRI: well-defined lobulated lesion involving glutei, vastus lateralis, obturator externus muscles; ""sedimentation sign"" with multiple fluid-calcium levels; calcifications hypointense on T1 and T2; fluid hypointense on T1, hyperintense on T2; heterogeneous contrast enhancement.  
  - CT: multilobulated calcific mass without bone/joint involvement.  
- Histopathology: fibro-collagenous tissue with granular calcifications in lobules, multinucleated giant cells, foamy macrophages, lymphocytes, plasma cells.  

B) Candidate pass/fail:  
1) Soft tissue sarcoma:  
   - Pros: Soft tissue mass with heterogeneous enhancement.  
   - Cons: Lack of aggressive bone/joint invasion; presence of multilobulated calcifications with fluid levels is uncommon; histology not consistent with malignancy.  

2) Myositis ossificans:  
   - Pros: Soft tissue mass with calcifications.  
   - Cons: Typically shows zonal ossification pattern; usually following trauma; no mention of peripheral maturation; no fluid-calcium levels or sedimentation sign; usually younger post-trauma scenario.  

3) CPPD disease:  
   - Pros: Can cause periarticular calcifications.  
   - Cons: Usually linear chondrocalcinosis in cartilage; uncommon multilobulated periarticular calcific masses; patient age young; serum phosphorus not typically elevated.  

4) Hydroxyapatite deposition disease:  
   - Pros: Periarticular calcifications possible.  
   - Cons: Usually smaller calcific deposits; no multilobulated mass with fluid levels; typical in shoulder; no elevated phosphorus.  

5) Hyperparathyroidism:  
   - Pros: Periarticular calcifications possible; can cause bone changes.  
   - Cons: Calcium levels normal; PTH normal; no bone/joint involvement; no metabolic findings.  

6) Primary hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis:  
   - Pros: Patient age, chronic periarticular multilobulated calcific masses, elevated serum phosphorus, normal calcium and PTH, sedimentation sign on MRI, histology typical with lobulated calcifications and giant cells.  
   - Cons: None significant.  

7) Synovial osteochondromatosis:  
   - Pros: Joint involvement with calcified loose bodies.  
   - Cons: Usually intra-articular, multiple ossified nodules; no mention of joint space involvement here; fluid levels not typical; histology not consistent.  

C) Ranking:  
1) Primary hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis (matches age, labs, imaging, histology).  
2) Myositis ossificans (possible but lacks classic imaging and clinical features).  
3) Synovial osteochondromatosis (less likely due to extra-articular location).  
4) Soft tissue sarcoma (less likely due to non-aggressive imaging and histology).  
5) Hyperparathyroidism (lab values rule out).  
6) CPPD disease (clinical and imaging features inconsistent).  
7) Hydroxyapatite deposition disease (does not fit morphology or biochemistry).  

Final diagnosis: Primary hyperphosphatemic tumoral calcinosis  
