18915,"Clinical History: Our patient is a 64-year-old male admitted to the intensive care unit (ICU) due to a prolonged cardiac arrest, who was on mechanical circulatory support with extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO). He was COVID-19-negative and presented with an encephalopathic syndrome.
 Imaging Findings: A brain magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) was performed, and the susceptibility-weighted imaging sequence (SWI), revealed multiple small hypointense foci consistent with cerebral microbleeds (CBMs). These lesions were diffusely distributed across the subcortical white matter, splenium of the corpus callosum and posterior fossa, affecting the brainstem (midbrain and pons), as well as both cerebellar hemispheres. The cortex and periventricular regions were spared (Figures 1a, 1b, and 1c). In addition, we found small watershed infarctions (Figures 2a and 2b).","Clinical History: Our patient is a 64-year-old male admitted to the intensive care unit (ICU) due to a prolonged cardiac arrest, who was on mechanical circulatory support with extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO). He was COVID-19-negative and presented with an encephalopathic syndrome.
 Imaging Findings: A brain magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) was performed, and the susceptibility-weighted imaging sequence (SWI), revealed multiple small hypointense foci consistent with cerebral microbleeds (CBMs). These lesions were diffusely distributed across the subcortical white matter, splenium of the corpus callosum and posterior fossa, affecting the brainstem (midbrain and pons), as well as both cerebellar hemispheres. The cortex and periventricular regions were spared. In addition, we found small watershed infarctions.","Critical illness-associate cerebral microbleeds, Hypertensive encephalopathy, Cerebral amyloid angiopathy, Fat-emboli, COVID-19",Critical illness-associate cerebral microbleeds,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>  
A) Key findings:  
- Patient is a 64-year-old male, prolonged cardiac arrest, on ECMO support, encephalopathic, COVID-19-negative.  
- MRI with susceptibility-weighted imaging (SWI) shows multiple small hypointense foci consistent with cerebral microbleeds.  
- Distribution of microbleeds: diffusely across subcortical white matter, splenium of corpus callosum, posterior fossa (brainstem: midbrain and pons), and cerebellar hemispheres.  
- Sparing of cortex and periventricular regions.  
- Presence of small watershed infarctions.

B) Candidate pass/fail:  

1) Critical illness-associated cerebral microbleeds  
- Pros: Consistent with typical distribution of microbleeds in critical illness (subcortical white matter, corpus callosum, brainstem, cerebellum); patient has prolonged critical illness and ECMO support, a known risk factor.  
- Cons: None significant; matches closely.

2) Hypertensive encephalopathy  
- Pros: Hypertensive encephalopathy can cause microbleeds, often in basal ganglia, thalamus, brainstem, cerebellum.  
- Cons: The distribution is more subcortical and corpus callosum-centric rather than deep structures; no mention of hypertension or typical hypertensive changes; cortex spared is consistent but the pattern is less classic.

3) Cerebral amyloid angiopathy  
- Pros: Causes lobar microbleeds.  
- Cons: Typically involves cortical and lobar microbleeds with sparing of deep structures; patient is younger (though 64 is possible), and distribution does not match classic CAA pattern; also, presence in brainstem and cerebellum is unusual.

4) Fat-emboli  
- Pros: Can cause multifocal microhemorrhages.  
- Cons: Typically associated with trauma or orthopedic surgery; no history given; pattern is usually diffuse and random, not localized to white matter/subcortical and corpus callosum; rare in this setting.

5) COVID-19  
- Pros: COVID-19 has been linked to cerebral microbleeds.  
- Cons: Patient is COVID-19-negative; thus, less likely.

C) Ranking:  
1) Critical illness-associated cerebral microbleeds – The pattern of microbleeds (subcortical white matter, splenium of corpus callosum, brainstem, cerebellum), the clinical context (ICU, prolonged cardiac arrest, ECMO), and the absence of cortical involvement make this diagnosis most consistent and specific.  
2) Hypertensive encephalopathy – Although possible, there is no evidence of history or imaging findings typical for hypertensive changes; distribution isn't typical for hypertension-related microbleeds.  
3) Cerebral amyloid angiopathy – Distribution and patient age less typical; cortex spared argues against CAA.  
