18932,"Clinical History: A 42-year-old male driver presented with insidious onset pain and effusion of the right knee for 3 weeks. The patient had a similar history the previous year, which resolved after taking nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs). The knee range of motion was terminally painful. There was no history of trauma, arthritis or comorbidities.
 Imaging Findings: Radiographs of the right knee revealed normal bone density without fracture or erosion. MRI of the right knee revealed patchy areas in the epimetaphyseal region of both the femoral condyles, showing hyperintense signals on proton density fat-suppressed (PDFS) images (Figure 1) and correlating hypointense signals on T1W images (Figure 2), suggestive of marrow oedema. Mild knee joint effusion was noted without synovial thickening, erosions or low signal lines. The ligaments and menisci were normal. The tibial condyles, fibula and patella showed normal marrow signal intensity. The articular cartilage, posteromedial and posterolateral corners of the knee joint were normal.","Clinical History: A 42-year-old male driver presented with insidious onset pain and effusion of the right knee for 3 weeks. The patient had a similar history the previous year, which resolved after taking nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs). The knee range of motion was terminally painful. There was no history of trauma, arthritis or comorbidities.
