4) Bone marrow oedema syndrome (BMES)  
- Pros: classic age group (mid-adult), insidious onset, focal marrow edema patchy in epimetaphyseal femoral condyles, mild effusion, no fractures, erosions, or joint pathology; resolves with NSAIDs; recurrent episodes common.  
- Cons: None.  
5) Stress fracture  
- Pros: marrow edema can be early sign.  
- Cons: no low signal fracture line; no pain related to activity; symmetrical involvement not typical; no history of trauma or overuse; normal bone density.

C) Ranking:  
1) Bone marrow oedema syndrome - most consistent with clinical and imaging findings.  
2) Inflammatory arthritis - less likely due to absence of typical inflammatory changes.  
3) Osteonecrosis - less likely due to absence of typical low signal lines or subchondral changes.  
4) Complex regional pain syndrome - less likely; no CRPS features mentioned.  
