18935,"Clinical History: A 51-year-old male patient presented with right-sided limb weakness and slurred speech for a month. No vomiting/seizures/syncope was reported.
 Imaging Findings: MRI showed a well-defined lesion in the left periventricular region, measuring 1.8 x 1.5 x 1.6 cm (AP x ML x CC) with significant perifocal oedema (Figure 1). The lesion was T2 hetero-intense (Figure 1) with a T2 hypointense and T1 hyperintense rim (Figure 2), showing diffusion restriction (Figure 4). Associated mass effects noted were midline shift to the right, left uncal herniation, and effacement of the left lateral ventricle (Figure 6). Extensive vasogenic oedema was noted involving the left gangliocapsular region, left frontotemporal lobe, left hemi-midbrain, and left hemi-pons (Figure 1). On post-contrast images, the lesion showed heterogenous enhancement with involvement of the left lateral ventricular margin (Figure 3).
 
 Tractography showed interruption of white matter tracts in the region of the lesion (Figure 5a). The region of perilesional oedema showed only deviation of the left internal capsule and left superior longitudinal fasciculus tracts (Figure 5a), explaining the patient’s symptoms. Fractional anisotropy was decreased (Figure 5b) while mean diffusivity was increased (Figure 5c) within the lesion and in the region of perilesional oedema.
 
 The patient then underwent left FP craniotomy and excision of the lesion.","Clinical History: A 51-year-old male patient presented with right-sided limb weakness and slurred speech for a month. No vomiting/seizures/syncope was reported.
 Imaging Findings: MRI showed a well-defined lesion in the left periventricular region, measuring 1.8 x 1.5 x 1.6 cm (AP x ML x CC) with significant perifocal oedema. The lesion was T2 hetero-intense with a T2 hypointense and T1 hyperintense rim, showing diffusion restriction. Associated mass effects noted were midline shift to the right, left uncal herniation, and effacement of the left lateral ventricle. Extensive vasogenic oedema was noted involving the left gangliocapsular region, left frontotemporal lobe, left hemi-midbrain, and left hemi-pons. On post-contrast images, the lesion showed heterogenous enhancement with involvement of the left lateral ventricular margin. Tractography showed interruption of white matter tracts in the region of the lesion. The region of perilesional oedema showed only deviation of the left internal capsule and left superior longitudinal fasciculus tracts, explaining the patient’s symptoms. Fractional anisotropy was decreased while mean diffusivity was increased within the lesion and in the region of perilesional oedema. The patient then underwent left FP craniotomy and excision of the lesion.","High-grade glioma, Solitary brain metastasis, Intracranial tuberculoma, Infective aetiology (tuberculous/fungal)",Intracranial tuberculoma,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>  
A) Key findings:  
- 51-year-old male with right-sided limb weakness and slurred speech (left periventricular lesion location correlates clinically).  
- Well-defined lesion in left periventricular area, 1.8 x 1.5 x 1.6 cm, with significant perifocal edema.  
- T2 heterogeneously intense with a T2 hypointense rim and T1 hyperintense rim, showing diffusion restriction within rim.  
- Heterogeneous post-contrast enhancement, involving left lateral ventricular margin.  
- Mass effect with midline shift, uncal herniation, effacement of left lateral ventricle.  
- Extensive vasogenic edema involving left basal ganglia, frontotemporal lobe, midbrain, and pons.  
- Tractography showing interruption of white matter tracts at lesion, but only deviation in perilesional edema.  
- FA decreased and MD increased in lesion and surrounding edema.  
- Surgery performed, excised lesion.  

B) Candidate pass/fail:  
1) High-grade glioma  
- Pros: Lesion with mass effect, diffusion restriction, heterogeneous enhancement, perilesional edema, disruption of white matter tracts, typical imaging features. Located in left periventricular region which is common for gliomas.  
- Cons: T2 hypointense and T1 hyperintense rim is not classic for glioma. Usually central necrosis may cause T2 heterogeneity but T1 hyperintense rim is unusual. Rim typically not hypointense on T2.  

2) Solitary brain metastasis  
- Pros: Well-defined lesion, heterogeneous enhancement, vasogenic edema, diffusion restriction in rim, mass effect common in metastases.  
- Cons: No known primary cancer history reported; metastases often more multiple; T1 hyperintense rim uncommon; tumor location is periventricular which is less common but possible.  

3) Intracranial tuberculoma  
- Pros: Well-defined lesion with T2 hypointense rim (caseating necrosis), T1 hyperintense rim, heterogeneous enhancement, significant edema, diffusion restriction in rim (caseous necrosis can restrict diffusion). Involvement of ventricular margin also possible. Clinical presentation with chronic symptoms over a month fits slow-growing lesion.  
- Cons: Usually TB lesions show T2 hyposignal center with ring enhancement; no systemic TB symptoms reported; patient age 51 maybe older but still possible.  

4) Infective aetiology (tuberculous/fungal)  
- Pros: Similar to tuberculoma, fungi can have T2 hypointense rims and T1 hyperintense rims, with ring enhancement and diffusion restriction. Chronic presentation with edema and mass effect fits.  
- Cons: Not enough specific data to favor fungal over tuberculoma; no systemic infection signs.

C) Ranking:  
1) Intracranial tuberculoma – T2 hypointense rim with T1 hyperintense rim and diffusion restriction in ring is classic for tuberculoma with caseating necrosis. Perilesional edema and mass effect fit.  
2) Infective aetiology (tuberculous/fungal) – Similar imaging findings, but less specific; tuberculoma more likely given rim signal characteristics.  
3) High-grade glioma – Mass effect, edema, tract disruption consistent but T1 hyperintense rim less typical.  
4) Solitary brain metastasis – Less likely without known primary; rim and diffusion restriction less typical.

