18939,"Clinical History: A 20-year-old woman came to the emergency department with complaints of multiple bone pains. She reported fractures of the right forearm and the right leg three years ago, occurring without any significant trauma. Laboratory findings revealed elevated alkaline phosphatase (ALP > 1400) and parathyroid hormone (720 pg/ml), serum calcium level was 10.8 mg/dl, and serum creatinine level was 0.9. There was no skin lesion.
 Imaging Findings: Skeletal Survey (Radiograph of the skull, dorso-lumbar spine and both upper and lower extremities)
 
 The shafts of the long bones showed ground glass opacities with expansion of the medullary cavity and thinning of the cortex. There were multiple lytic lesions in the shaft of the long bones, and a few of them showed a sclerotic rim. There were areas of sclerosis in the metaphysis of the long bones (Figures 1a, 1b, 1c, and 1d). The dorsal lumbar spine showed reduced bone density with endplate sclerosis, consistent with a rugger-jersey spine (Figure 2b). Multiple lytic lesions were seen in the scapula, ribs, clavicle, multiple vertebral bodies, pelvic bones and metacarpals on both sides (Figures 2a and 2c). There was subperiosteal resorption on the radial aspect of the head of the second proximal phalanx (Figure 3). Skull radiograph showed a widening of the diploic spaces with multiple well-defined, variable-sized sclerotic lesions (Figure 4).
 
 CT Brain
 
 The CT brain revealed a widening of diploic spaces with multiple well-defined sclerotic and ground glass density lesions (Figures 5a, 5b, and 5c).
 
 USG Neck
 
 In the US of the neck, there was a well-defined heterogeneously hypoechoic lesion posterior to the right lobe of the thyroid (Figure 6).
 
 CT Parathyroid Protocol
 
 A hypodense enhancing lesion posterior to the right lobe of the thyroid was detected, suggestive of parathyroid adenoma (Figures 7a, 7b, 8a, 8b, 9a, 9b, 9c).","Clinical History: A 20-year-old woman came to the emergency department with complaints of multiple bone pains. She reported fractures of the right forearm and the right leg three years ago, occurring without any significant trauma. Laboratory findings revealed elevated alkaline phosphatase (ALP > 1400) and parathyroid hormone (720 pg/ml), serum calcium level was 10.8 mg/dl, and serum creatinine level was 0.9. There was no skin lesion.
 
 Imaging Findings: Skeletal survey radiographs of the skull, dorso-lumbar spine, and both upper and lower extremities showed that the shafts of the long bones had ground glass opacities with expansion of the medullary cavity and thinning of the cortex. There were multiple lytic lesions in the shafts of the long bones, and a few of them had a sclerotic rim. There were areas of sclerosis in the metaphysis of the long bones. The dorsal lumbar spine showed reduced bone density with endplate sclerosis, consistent with a rugger-jersey spine. Multiple lytic lesions were seen in the scapula, ribs, clavicle, multiple vertebral bodies, pelvic bones and metacarpals on both sides. There was subperiosteal resorption on the radial aspect of the head of the second proximal phalanx. Skull radiograph showed a widening of the diploic spaces with multiple well-defined, variable-sized sclerotic lesions. CT brain revealed a widening of diploic spaces with multiple well-defined sclerotic and ground glass density lesions. In the ultrasound of the neck, there was a well-defined heterogeneously hypoechoic lesion posterior to the right lobe of the thyroid. On CT parathyroid protocol, a hypodense enhancing lesion posterior to the right lobe of the thyroid was detected, suggestive of parathyroid adenoma.","Primary hyperparathyroidism with fibrous dysplasia of bone, Paget’s disease of bone",Primary hyperparathyroidism with fibrous dysplasia of bone,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>  
A) Key findings:  
- Young adult female (20 years old) with multiple spontaneous fractures and bone pains.  
- Laboratory: Elevated ALP (>1400 IU/L), markedly elevated PTH (720 pg/ml), mildly elevated serum calcium (10.8 mg/dl), normal creatinine.  
- Radiographs show:  
  - Long bone shafts with ground glass opacities, medullary expansion, cortical thinning.  
  - Multiple lytic lesions with sclerotic rims in long bones.  
  - Subperiosteal resorption (classic for hyperparathyroidism) on the radial aspect of the phalanx.  
  - Rugger-jersey spine (endplate sclerosis in lumbar vertebrae).  
  - Sclerosis in metaphysis and multiple small sclerotic/ground glass lesions in skull and other bones.  
- CT brain confirms skull changes with diploic space widening and sclerotic/ground glass lesions.  
- Neck ultrasound and CT parathyroid protocol show a right-sided parathyroid adenoma.

B) Candidate pass/fail:  
- Primary hyperparathyroidism with fibrous dysplasia of bone:  
  Pros: Presence of parathyroid adenoma explaining hyperparathyroidism with elevated PTH and calcium; classic bone changes in hyperparathyroidism (subperiosteal resorption, rugger-jersey spine, brown tumours/lytic lesions). The ground glass and sclerotic lesions might be interpreted as fibrous dysplasia, but the diffuse nature and other hyperparathyroidism findings must be considered.  
  Cons: Fibrous dysplasia classically involves jaw, pelvis, ribs, and long bones and presents with ground glass appearance, but the presence of multiple lytic lesions with sclerotic rims consistent with brown tumors, elevated PTH, and parathyroid adenoma argues against fibrous dysplasia alone.  

- Paget’s disease of bone:  
  Pros: Rugger jersey spine and mixed lytic-sclerotic lesions can be seen in Paget's.  
  Cons: Young age not typical (Paget's usually >50 years). No mention of typical Paget’s bone expansion and deformities, no characteristic ""cotton wool"" skull, no history of raised ALP without hyperparathyroidism findings. No parathyroid lesions or elevated PTH. Subperiosteal resorption and parathyroid adenoma are not features of Paget's.

C) Ranking:  
1) Primary hyperparathyroidism with fibrous dysplasia of bone - This matches hyperparathyroidism labs with parathyroid adenoma and bone changes including brown tumors (lytic lesions with sclerotic rims) and also explains ground glass appearances that are seen in fibrous dysplasia, but the hyperparathyroidism findings are dominant.  
2) Paget’s disease of bone - Less likely due to age, absence of classic Paget’s features, and presence of hyperparathyroidism signs not seen in Paget’s.  

Thus, the best fit is primary hyperparathyroidism with fibrous dysplasia of bone.  
</analysis>  
