18940,"Clinical History: A 36-year-old woman presented with permanent pain of increasing intensity in her right leg that had been evolving for 24 hours. The pain appeared immediately following a horse ride in an improperly adjusted stirrup and was not relieved by paracetamol, ketoprofen and morphine. No significant medical history.
 Imaging Findings: MRI of the legs showed a swollen appearance of the right anterolateral compartment muscles with:
 
 Fat-suppressed coronal T2-weighted (Figure 1) and axial PD-SPIR (Figure 2) emphasised the acute involvement of the lateral compartment of the leg through a noticeable bulging of the compartment muscles, which is clearly visible in the axial view when compared to the healthy contralateral side. Additional loss of fascicular architecture is seen. Diffuse hyperintensity of the compartment indicates muscular oedema.
 
 Sagittal T1-weighted sequence showed slight spontaneous high signal intensity within the involved muscles (Figure 3).
 
 After injection, the fat-suppressed axial T1-weighted sequence (Figure 4) showed focal defects of enhancement within the proximal portion of the muscles, indicating areas of ischemia.
 
 No other causes of acute pain, including a stress fracture, deep vein thrombosis or focal muscular strain, were identified on the examination. The diagnosis of acute compartment syndrome was confirmed by MRI.","Clinical History: A 36-year-old woman presented with permanent pain of increasing intensity in her right leg that had been evolving for 24 hours. The pain appeared immediately following a horse ride in an improperly adjusted stirrup and was not relieved by paracetamol, ketoprofen and morphine. No significant medical history.
