- Pros: Age compatible; expansile lytic lesion; multiple cystic areas with blood products; often eccentric and can involve sacrum; soft tissue component possible.  
- Cons: Usually well-defined and expansile without aggressive cortical breach or soft tissue mass; nerve root involvement less common; diffusion restriction and heterogeneous enhancement less typical; erosion of SI joint and extensive soft tissue infiltration less typical for simple ABC.  
3) Giant cell tumour (GCT)  
- Pros: Occurs in adolescence; typically epiphyseal involving sacrum; lytic lesion; can extend to soft tissue; can involve neural foramina.  
- Cons: Usually more homogeneous on MRI; lack of cystic hemorrhagic spaces typical of ABC or telangiectatic osteosarcoma; less likely to have prominent blood degradation products; soft tissue mass less common and less hemorrhagic; usually not diffusely hyperintense T1.

C) Ranking with tie-breaks:  
1) Telangiectatic osteosarcoma: Most compatible with hemorrhagic cystic spaces, aggressive behavior, diffusion restriction, soft tissue extension, and neural canal involvement.  
2) Aneurysmal bone cyst: Compatible but tends to be less aggressive, less soft tissue mass, and less neural canal involvement.  
3) Giant cell tumour: Less likely given hemorrhagic cysts and diffusion restriction.  

Conclusion: The imaging characteristics (hemorrhagic cystic spaces, aggressive bone destruction, soft tissue extension, neural foraminal involvement, diffusion restriction, heterogeneous enhancement) in a 13-year-old strongly favor telangiectatic osteosarcoma.  
