18957,"Clinical History: A 25-year-old male patient with no significant past medical background is referred for left knee pain since the age of 10, associated with knee swelling. Since then, he has always maintained complaints but lived a normal life. Plain radiograph, CT scan and MR were ordered for further investigation.
 Imaging Findings: On plain film (Figures 1a, 1b, 1c, and 1d), there are periosteal and endosteal cortical thickening associated with extra-cortical bone formation along the anterior aspect of the left tibia and the medial aspect of the left femur. Areas of central medullary hyperostosis can be observed in the inferior third of the femoral diaphysis and in the femoral head. The lesions have an appearance that resembles “flowing candle wax”.
 
 CT scan (Figures 2a, 2b, 2c, 2d, and 2e) allows for further acknowledgement of the changes described above.
 
 MR performed on a 1.5T MR scanner (T1 and STIR sequences in axial and coronal planes; Figures 3a and 3b) depict extensive changes with very low signal on all imaging sequences, mainly involving the left femur and tibia, with diffuse thickening of the bone cortex giving the bone surface a wavy appearance, as well as multiple intramedullary foci showing marked hypointensity, indicating a strong component of bone sclerosis. The lesions show eccentric growth, extending from the diaphysis to the epiphysis, and exceeding the cortical surface.","Clinical History: A 25-year-old male patient with no significant past medical background is referred for left knee pain since the age of 10, associated with knee swelling. Since then, he has always maintained complaints but lived a normal life. Plain radiograph, CT scan and MR were ordered for further investigation.
 Imaging Findings: On plain film, there are periosteal and endosteal cortical thickening associated with extra-cortical bone formation along the anterior aspect of the left tibia and the medial aspect of the left femur. Areas of central medullary hyperostosis can be observed in the inferior third of the femoral diaphysis and in the femoral head. The lesions have an appearance that resembles “flowing candle wax”. CT scan allows for further acknowledgement of the changes described above. MR performed on a 1.5T MR scanner (T1 and STIR sequences in axial and coronal planes) depict extensive changes with very low signal on all imaging sequences, mainly involving the left femur and tibia, with diffuse thickening of the bone cortex giving the bone surface a wavy appearance, as well as multiple intramedullary foci showing marked hypointensity, indicating a strong component of bone sclerosis. The lesions show eccentric growth, extending from the diaphysis to the epiphysis, and exceeding the cortical surface.","Progressive diaphyseal dysplasia, Hereditary multiple diaphyseal sclerosis, Polyostotic melorheostosis, Erdheim–Chester disease, Parosteal osteosarcoma",Polyostotic melorheostosis,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>  
A) Key findings:  
- Young adult male (25 years) with history of left knee pain and swelling from age 10.  
- Imaging shows periosteal and endosteal cortical thickening with extra-cortical bone formation on anterior tibia and medial femur.  
- Central medullary hyperostosis in femoral diaphysis and head.  
- Classic ""flowing candle wax"" appearance described on radiographs and confirmed by CT.  
- MRI shows extensive low signal on T1 and STIR, indicating sclerosis, thickened cortex, eccentric growth from diaphysis to epiphysis extending beyond cortical surface.  
- Unilateral left sided involvement (femur and tibia).  

B) Candidate pass/fail with 1-2 pros/cons:  
1) Progressive diaphyseal dysplasia (Camurati-Engelmann disease):  
- Pros: Cortical thickening and diaphyseal involvement can be seen.  
- Cons: Usually bilateral symmetric diaphyseal diaphyseal expansion with diffuse osteosclerosis, not typically ""flowing candle wax"" appearance; involves diaphyses symmetrically; no periosteal hyperostosis and extra-cortical bone formation; typically painful and muscular weakness.  

2) Hereditary multiple diaphyseal sclerosis (RMND):  
- Pros: Multiple diaphyseal sclerosis, cortical thickening.  
- Cons: Typically symmetric, bilateral, and less flamboyant periosteal reaction; no characteristic ""flowing candle wax"" pattern; rare and less well documented for such dramatic periosteal hyperostosis and extension beyond cortex.  

3) Polyostotic melorheostosis:  
- Pros: Classic ""flowing candle wax"" hyperostosis; unilateral (segmental) periosteal bone formation; involvement of diaphysis and epiphysis; cortical thickening with extra-cortical bone formation; sclerotic intramedullary foci; young patient with chronic pain and swelling; unilaterally involves tibia and femur.  
- Cons: None significant; fits the description well.  

4) ErdheimÂChester disease:  
- Pros: Can cause symmetric diaphyseal sclerosis and periosteal reaction.  
- Cons: Usually bilateral, symmetric, systemic involvement (including long bones symmetrically; often ribs, pelvis, etc.); no typical ""candle wax"" periosteal bone formation; more systemic and involves other organs; patient younger and unilateral involvement makes this less likely.  

5) Parosteal osteosarcoma:  
- Pros: Usually involves metaphyseal regions; can have cortical thickening and extra-cortical bone.  
- Cons: Typically unilateral but limited to one site; malignant lesion with aggressive periosteal reaction, but not the classic ""candle wax"" flowing hyperostosis; chronic presentation from age 10 unlikely; MR shows low signal consistent with sclerosis rather than aggressive tumor pattern.  

C) Ranking:  
1) Polyostotic melorheostosis (classic ""flowing candle wax"" appearance, unilateral periosteal hyperostosis, matches age and symptoms).  
2) Hereditary multiple diaphyseal sclerosis (less flamboyant, less typical).  
3) Progressive diaphyseal dysplasia (symmetrical, diaphyseal only).  
4) Erdheim-Chester disease (bilateral, systemic).  
5) Parosteal osteosarcoma (malignant pattern not fitting chronic slow course).  
Thus, the imaging pattern and clinical course best match polyostotic melorheostosis.  

</analysis>  
<final>  
Polyostotic melorheostosis  
