   Pros: Typically cortical, non-enhancing, often frontotemporal, may have calcifications.
   Cons: Usually pediatric/young adult. Usually shows a characteristic ""bubbly"" appearance on MRI. Bilateral lesions uncommon. Bleeding uncommon. Bone remodeling unusual.

6) Pleomorphic xanthoastrocytoma
   Pros: Cystic and solid components, superficial cortical and subcortical involvement, may have calcifications, minimal enhancement.
   Cons: Typically solitary, usually in young adults (<30), may enhance more. Bleeding less common. Bone remodeling rare.

