3) Pleomorphic xanthoastrocytoma – less likely due to age and bilateral lesions.
4) Diffuse astrocytoma – calcifications uncommon.
5) DNET – age and bilateral rare but possible.
6) Glioblastoma – less likely due to lack of typical aggressive features, unilateral involvement, and strong enhancement.

