19003,"Clinical History: A 39-year-old male, with no prior relevant medical history, presents with atraumatic intermittent sharp pain in the lower segment of the right anterior thoracic wall. The symptoms began two months earlier when the patient started exercising (CrossFit), mostly triggered by training (especially abdominal crunches) whilst being asymptomatic in normal daily activities.
 Imaging Findings: Ultrasound imaging of the costochondral region of the patient showed a normal arrangement of ribs and rib cartilage while the patient was in a supine position (Figure 1). No abnormalities in bone or cartilage contours, nor any soft tissue lesions were identified.
 
 Dynamic ultrasound of the symptomatic area, performed while the patient replicated the movement that elicits pain (abdominal crunches), revealed hypermobility of the 9th rib cartilage, which moved upwards and became pinned beneath the 8th rib cartilage (Figures 2 and 3). This triggered the pain, with a popping sensation associated. When the patient returned to the supine position, the 9th rib returned to its normal position (Figure 4).","Clinical History: A 39-year-old male, with no prior relevant medical history, presents with atraumatic intermittent sharp pain in the lower segment of the right anterior thoracic wall. The symptoms began two months earlier when the patient started exercising (CrossFit), mostly triggered by training (especially abdominal crunches) whilst being asymptomatic in normal daily activities.
 Imaging Findings: Ultrasound imaging of the costochondral region of the patient showed a normal arrangement of ribs and rib cartilage while the patient was in a supine position. No abnormalities in bone or cartilage contours, nor any soft tissue lesions were identified. Dynamic ultrasound of the symptomatic area, performed while the patient replicated the movement that elicits pain (abdominal crunches), revealed hypermobility of the 9th rib cartilage, which moved upwards and became pinned beneath the 8th rib cartilage. This triggered the pain, with a popping sensation associated. When the patient returned to the supine position, the 9th rib returned to its normal position.","Tietze syndrome, Costochondritis, Rib fracture, Slipping rib syndrome, Pleuritic pain, Sternalis syndrome",Slipping rib syndrome,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis> 
A) Key findings: 
- 39-year-old male with atraumatic intermittent sharp pain in the lower segment of the right anterior thoracic wall.
- Pain triggered by exercise (abdominal crunches), asymptomatic at rest.
- Ultrasound in supine position: normal ribs and rib cartilage; no bone/cartilage or soft tissue abnormalities.
- Dynamic ultrasound during pain-provoking movement shows hypermobility of the 9th rib cartilage, moving upwards and getting trapped (""pinned"") beneath the 8th rib cartilage, causing popping sensation and pain.
- The rib reverts to normal position when the movement ceases.

B) Candidate pass/fail:
1) Tietze syndrome:
   - Pros: Presents with chest wall pain.
   - Cons: Typically shows swelling and tenderness of the costochondral junction, often with ultrasound or imaging findings (e.g., cartilage swelling); dynamic rib movement is not a feature. No swelling reported here.
  
2) Costochondritis:
   - Pros: Common cause of anterior chest wall pain; inflammation of costochondral junction can cause pain aggravated by movement or palpation.
   - Cons: No imaging evidence of inflammation or bone/cartilage abnormality; no mention of tenderness or swelling; dynamic rib movement/ hypermobility not a characteristic feature.
  
3) Rib fracture:
   - Pros: Can cause localized chest wall pain.
   - Cons: No evidence of fracture on imaging; pain is intermittent and movement-related rather than constant; no trauma history.
  
4) Slipping rib syndrome:
   - Pros: Characterized by hypermobility of the lower costal cartilage causing pain and a popping sensation; pain triggered by movement; dynamic imaging showing rib displacement pinning under adjacent rib cartilage. Classic for lower costal cartilages (8th-10th ribs) on the right side.
   - Cons: None, fully compatible with dynamic findings and clinical presentation.
  
5) Pleuritic pain:
   - Pros: Sharp chest pain.
   - Cons: Typically worsened by respiration or deep breathing rather than chest wall movement; no imaging correlation with rib/cartilage mobility; no pleural pathology reported.
  
6) Sternalis syndrome:
   - Pros: Rare cause of chest pain.
   - Cons: Involves sternal muscle variant (sternalis) causing chest discomfort or pain; no relation to rib mobility or dynamic movement described here.

C) Ranking:
1) Slipping rib syndrome - pathognomonic dynamic hypermobility of 9th rib cartilage pinning under 8th rib cartilage with popping pain during movement.
2) Costochondritis - possible but lacks imaging signs, no inflammation noted.
3) Tietze syndrome - ruled out because no swelling or imaging abnormalities.
4) Pleuritic pain - less likely given no pleural signs and pain triggered by muscle movement not respiration.
5) Rib fracture - no trauma or imaging evidence.
6) Sternalis syndrome - no imaging or clinical correlation.

<final>Slipping rib syndrome</final>
