19008,"Clinical History: A 47-year-old man presented with a history of weakness in the right arm since a few weeks. There was a history of a road traffic accident two months back.
 Imaging Findings: MRI of the brachial plexus showed a pre-fixed plexus with supply from the C4 nerve root. There was diffuse oedema in the C4–C6 nerve roots with thickening of the C5 and C6 nerve roots and the superior trunk (Figures 1a, 1b, and 2c). The nerve roots were hyperintense on T2 sequences and bulky as compared to the contralateral side (Figures 2a and 2b). There was oedematous thickening of the right axillary nerve throughout its course with subacute denervation oedema in the deltoid and the teres minor muscles (Figures 3a, 3b, and 3c). Subacute denervation with grade I fatty infiltration is also noted in the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles.","Clinical History: A 47-year-old man presented with a history of weakness in the right arm since a few weeks. There was a history of a road traffic accident two months back.
 Imaging Findings: MRI of the brachial plexus showed a pre-fixed plexus with supply from the C4 nerve root. There was diffuse oedema in the C4–C6 nerve roots with thickening of the C5 and C6 nerve roots and the superior trunk. The nerve roots were hyperintense on T2 sequences and bulky as compared to the contralateral side. There was oedematous thickening of the right axillary nerve throughout its course with subacute denervation oedema in the deltoid and the teres minor muscles. Subacute denervation with grade I fatty infiltration is also noted in the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles.","Traumatic brachial plexopathy, Brachial plexitis, Thoracic outlet syndrome, Cervical radiculopathy",Traumatic brachial plexopathy,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis> 
A) Key findings: 
- 47-year-old man with right arm weakness developing weeks after a road traffic accident.
- MRI brachial plexus shows a pre-fixed plexus (i.e., anatomy variant where plexus is formed by roots including C4 rather than typical C5 start).
- Diffuse oedema and thickening of C4âC6 nerve roots, specifically C5 and C6 and superior trunk.
- Nerve roots hyperintense on T2 and bulky compared to contralateral side.
- Oedematous thickening of right axillary nerve throughout its course.
- Subacute denervation oedema in deltoid and teres minor muscles.
- Subacute denervation with grade I fatty infiltration in supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles.

B) Candidate pass/fail:
1) Traumatic brachial plexopathy: 
   - Pros: History of recent road traffic accident; MRI shows thickened, oedematous nerve roots and trunks; subacute denervation changes in muscles consistent with nerve injury; involvement of multiple nerve roots and trunks fits traumatic plexus injury.
   - Cons: None significant; fits trauma timeline.

2) Brachial plexitis: 
   - Pros: MRI oedema and thickening of nerve roots and trunks; T2 hyperintensity is typical for inflammatory plexitis; muscle denervation changes are consistent.
   - Cons: No mention of inflammation or pain typical of plexitis; recent trauma favors trauma over idiopathic/inflammatory cause.

3) Thoracic outlet syndrome: 
   - Pros: Involves brachial plexus; can cause denervation changes.
   - Cons: Usually chronic, no acute postoperative or traumatic history; nerve thickening and oedema on MRI not typical; no bony or compressive lesion mentioned; acute/subacute presentation unlikely.

4) Cervical radiculopathy: 
   - Pros: C5, C6 roots involved.
   - Cons: Radiculopathy mainly involves single root; here multiple roots and superior trunk involved; also axillary nerve involvement and muscle changes extend beyond radicular distribution; trauma and plexus changes not consistent with simple radiculopathy.

C) Ranking:
1) Traumatic brachial plexopathy â matches trauma history, MRI findings in nerve roots and trunks, and denervation in nerves downstream.
2) Brachial plexitis â MRI features similar but history favors trauma.
3) Thoracic outlet syndrome â less likely due to acute timeline and lack of compressive findings.
4) Cervical radiculopathy â excluded due to plexus involvement beyond roots and trauma history.

Thus, the best diagnosis is Traumatic brachial plexopathy because the clinical history (recent RTA), imaging (thickening and edema in nerve roots and superior trunk), and muscle denervation pattern fit trauma-related plexus injury.

