   - Pros: Can occur in pelvis; hypervascular; well-defined.  
   - Cons: Typically less common in mesorectal space; variable imaging features; no specific hypervascular hallmark; less common than GIST here.  

7) Fibroma:  
   - Pros: Benign fibrous tumor can be well-defined.  
   - Cons: Typically not hypervascular; usually less symptomatic; rare in mesorectal space.  

8) Fibrosarcoma:  
   - Pros: Malignant fibroblastic tumor can be heterogeneous and hypervascular.  
   - Cons: Rare in mesorectal space; usually larger and more aggressive-appearing.  

9) Desmoid tumour:  
   - Pros: Common in mesentery/rectum; can cause mass effect; well-defined.  
   - Cons: Typically not hypervascular; usually solid and homogeneous; rarely cause ascites; more firm infiltrative than discrete mass.  

10) Haemangioma:  
    - Pros: Hypervascular lesion possible.  
    - Cons: Usually contains cystic spaces/vascular channels; location unusual; mass size and heterogeneity less typical; no feeding vessels or phleboliths noted.  

11) Angiosarcoma:  
    - Pros: Hypervascular, aggressive soft tissue tumor.  
    - Cons: Rare in mesorectal space; usually more infiltrative and irregular margins; often associated with hemorrhage/necrosis; usually larger and more aggressive.  

C) Ranking:  
1) Rectal gastrointestinal stromal tumour (GIST)  
   - Pathognomonic: Adjacent to rectum, hypervascular mass, weight loss/anemia present, consistent with typical GIST presentation.  
2) Leiomyosarcoma  
   - Compatible but less specific than GIST; less hallmark of rectal origin.  
3) Solitary fibrous tumour  
   - Possible but less likely given location and clinical presentation.  
4) Desmoid tumour  
   - Location possible but less hypervascular and less likely to cause systemic symptoms without infiltration.  
5) Angiosarcoma  
   - Possible but less common and less typical imaging.  
6) Fibrosarcoma, Fibroma  
   - Less likely given imaging and clinical.  
7) Leiomyoma  
   - Benign, size and symptoms less likely.  
8) Dedifferentiated liposarcoma  
   - No fat, less typical location.  
9) Angiomyolipoma, Haemangioma  
