Pros: Bilateral symmetrical involvement of the central pons and sometimes extrapontine areas like basal ganglia; can involve corpus callosum and corticospinal tracts. Chronic alcoholism and electrolyte disturbances can predispose.  
Cons: Usually history of rapid electrolyte correction or hyponatremia, which is not mentioned. No explicit mention of pontine involvement; corpus callosum involvement is less classic but possible.

3) Toxic-metabolic encephalopathy  
Pros: Can involve white matter and cortical regions with diffuse MRI changes. Chronic alcohol can be a toxin.  
Cons: Usually nonspecific diffusion changes without clear symmetrical corpus callosum involvement. This is very broad and not specific enough.

