19038,"Clinical History: A 29-year-old female patient presented to the cardiology department with episodes of numbness in both her upper and lower extremities, which spontaneously resolved after 30 minutes. She also reported episodes of chest pain that she attributed to stress. Heart auscultation was normal. ECG showed diffuse ST-elevations.
 Imaging Findings: Echocardiography (ECG) demonstrated severe systolic heart failure, with a left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) of 30%. The exam showed basal hypokinesia and preserved apical contractility, along with irregularities in the lining of the left ventricular myocardium (Figure 1).
 
 A contrast-enhanced computed tomography (CECT) scan revealed no coronary abnormalities but confirmed the irregularities in the left ventricle wall (Figure 2).
 
 Subsequently, a cardiac MRI was performed, which revealed moderate left ventricle dilation and irregularities in the ventricle wall, including protrusions of myocardial bridges, multiple crypts, and thinning of the inferolateral apex with diffuse dyskinesia (Figures 3 and 4). Severe left ventricular dysfunction was confirmed, with an LVEF of 20% and a global longitudinal strain (GLS) of -7.85%, as well as ventricular dyssynchrony. A non-ischemic fibrosis region was also present in the interventricular septum and the posterior hinge point. The right ventricle appeared to be normal in morphology and function.","Clinical History: A 29-year-old female patient presented to the cardiology department with episodes of numbness in both her upper and lower extremities, which spontaneously resolved after 30 minutes. She also reported episodes of chest pain that she attributed to stress. Heart auscultation was normal. ECG showed diffuse ST-elevations.
 Imaging Findings: Echocardiography (ECG) demonstrated severe systolic heart failure, with a left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) of 30%. The exam showed basal hypokinesia and preserved apical contractility, along with irregularities in the lining of the left ventricular myocardium. A contrast-enhanced computed tomography (CECT) scan revealed no coronary abnormalities but confirmed the irregularities in the left ventricle wall. Subsequently, a cardiac MRI was performed, which revealed moderate left ventricle dilation and irregularities in the ventricle wall, including protrusions of myocardial bridges, multiple crypts, and thinning of the inferolateral apex with diffuse dyskinesia. Severe left ventricular dysfunction was confirmed, with an LVEF of 20% and a global longitudinal strain (GLS) of -7.85%, as well as ventricular dyssynchrony. A non-ischemic fibrosis region was also present in the interventricular septum and the posterior hinge point. The right ventricle appeared to be normal in morphology and function.","Left ventricular noncompaction, Saw-tooth cardiomyopathy, Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, Arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy",Saw-tooth cardiomyopathy,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>  
A) Key findings:  
- 29-year-old female with episodic numbness and transient chest pain.  
- ECG: diffuse ST-elevations.  
- Echocardiography: severe systolic heart failure (LVEF 30%), basal hypokinesia with preserved apical contractility, myocardial wall irregularities.  
- CECT: no coronary artery disease, confirms LV wall irregularities.  
- Cardiac MRI: moderate LV dilation, myocardial wall irregularities including protrusions of myocardial bridges, multiple crypts, thinning of inferolateral apex with diffuse dyskinesia, severe LV dysfunction (LVEF 20%, GLS -7.85%), ventricular dyssynchrony, and non-ischemic fibrosis in interventricular septum and posterior hinge point. RV normal.  
- Clinical context: young patient, severe LV dysfunction, wall irregularities, crypts, fibrosis.  

B) Candidate pass/fail with 1â2 pros/cons each:  
1) Left ventricular noncompaction (LVNC):  
Pros: LV dilation, myocardial crypts, severe LV dysfunction, non-ischemic fibrosis, irregular endocardial/epicardial ratios known in LVNC.  
Cons: No explicit mention of prominent trabeculations or noncompacted to compacted ratio >2.3; protrusions of myocardial bridges less typical; basal hypokinesia with preserved apical contractility less characteristic.  

2) Saw-tooth cardiomyopathy:  
Pros: Very rare; described as LV wall irregularities producing sawtooth appearance; young patients; systolic dysfunction possible.  
Cons: Very rare and not well-described; clinical and imaging findings somewhat broad; no specific literature to support crypts or non-ischemic fibrosis pattern; episodic symptoms less typical.  

3) Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM):  
Pros: Presence of myocardial crypts commonly reported in HCM; fibrosis in hinge points typical.  
Cons: No mention of hypertrophy or asymmetric septal hypertrophy; LV dilation and severe systolic dysfunction less typical; basal hypokinesia more characteristic of tachycardia-induced or other cardiomyopathies.  

4) Arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy (ACM) - likely left-dominant:  
Pros: Fibrosis, ventricular dyskinesia, severe dysfunction fits ACM phenotype; myocardial irregularities and crypts possible; no coronary disease; episodic arrhythmogenic symptoms such as numbness possibly suggest arrhythmias; LV involvement with fibrosis and wall thinning common.  
Cons: RV normal, but left-dominant forms exist; myocardial bridges & crypts not classic but can be present in cardiomyopathies.  

C) Ranking with tie-breaks:  
1) Arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy: severe LV dysfunction, non-ischemic fibrosis, wall dyskinesia, absence of coronary disease, and basal hypokinesia; fits well with ACM's inflammatory/fibrotic process. RV normal does not exclude left-dominant ACM.  
2) Left ventricular noncompaction: LV dilation and crypts support LVNC, but no clear evidence of trabeculations or noncompaction ratio given; wall protrusions (myocardial bridges) less typical.  
3) Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy: fibrosis and crypts typical, but no hypertrophy or classic HCM features reported; systolic dysfunction severe and diffuse less typical.  
4) Saw-tooth cardiomyopathy: very rare and less described; not enough pathognomonic imaging features.  

Conclusion: Arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy best fits the combination of severe LV dysfunction, fibrosis, wall abnormalities, and absence of coronary disease.  

</analysis>  
