19047,"Clinical History: 8-year-old female with swelling in the dorsal aspect of the tongue on the left side, present since birth, with slight enlargement in the past 6 months. No history of fever, breathing difficulties, or bleeding tendency. On physical examination, it showed a bluish swelling in the anterior tongue measuring 1.5 x 1 cm, and it was a soft, non-tender mass on palpation (Figure 1).
 Imaging Findings: Ultrasound of the dorsal aspect of the tongue showed a well-circumscribed hypoechoic lesion with smooth margins in the anterior aspect of the tongue on the left side. No evidence of calcifications (phleboliths) or cystic areas. No surrounding induration was seen. Colour Doppler studies showed mild internal vascularity (Figure 2).
 
 MRI showed a well-defined T2 intensely hyperintense (Figures 3a, 3b, and 3c), and iso to slightly hyperintense signal in T1-weighted images (Figure 5) in the anterior aspect of the tongue on the left side. No blooming artefacts on the gradient echo sequences (GRE) images (Figure 4). No evidence of true diffusion restriction. Homogeneous contrast enhancement on post-contrast T1 images was seen (Figure 6). Delayed post-contrast images are not available due to patient motion artefacts.","Clinical History: 8-year-old female with swelling in the dorsal aspect of the tongue on the left side, present since birth, with slight enlargement in the past 6 months. No history of fever, breathing difficulties, or bleeding tendency. On physical examination, it showed a bluish swelling in the anterior tongue measuring 1.5 x 1 cm, and it was a soft, non-tender mass on palpation.
 
 Imaging Findings: Ultrasound of the dorsal aspect of the tongue showed a well-circumscribed hypoechoic lesion with smooth margins in the anterior aspect of the tongue on the left side. No evidence of calcifications (phleboliths) or cystic areas. No surrounding induration was seen. Colour Doppler studies showed mild internal vascularity. MRI showed a well-defined T2 intensely hyperintense, and iso to slightly hyperintense signal in T1-weighted images in the anterior aspect of the tongue on the left side. No blooming artefacts on the gradient echo sequences (GRE) images. No evidence of true diffusion restriction. Homogeneous contrast enhancement on post-contrast T1 images was seen. Delayed post-contrast images are not available due to patient motion artefacts.","Haemangioma, Lymphangioma, Kawasaki disease, Malignant melanoma",Haemangioma,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>  
A) Key findings:  
- Age and clinical context: 8-year-old female with a congenital swelling on the dorsal anterior left tongue, slowly enlarging over the past 6 months.  
- Physical exam: bluish, soft, non-tender, 1.5 x 1 cm mass.  
- Ultrasound: well-circumscribed hypoechoic lesion with smooth margins, mild internal vascularity, no calcifications or cystic areas.  
- MRI: well-defined lesion in anterior tongue left side, T2 hyperintense, T1 iso to slightly hyperintense, no blooming on GRE (no hemosiderin or calcification), no diffusion restriction, homogeneous post-contrast enhancement.  
- No surrounding induration or aggressive features.  

B) Candidate pass/fail:  
1) Haemangioma  
   - Pros: Common vascular lesion in pediatric patients, typically presents as a soft tissue mass, can be T2 hyperintense and shows internal vascularity on Doppler. Bluish discoloration can be seen clinically. Well-circumscribed lesion, homogeneous enhancement consistent.  
   - Cons: Usually, there may be phleboliths (calcifications), but none were seen here; however, not all haemangiomas have phleboliths. No mention of typical feeding/draining vessels. Age and presentation are consistent.  

2) Lymphangioma  
   - Pros: Can present as congenital lesions in the tongue, sometimes with a bluish hue; lesions often cystic and may have internal septations.  
   - Cons: Typically multilocular, cystic appearance on imaging (on US and MRI), often T2 hyperintense but with cystic spaces; here lesion is solid and well circumscribed, no cystic areas or septations, and mild vascularity is seen, which is less typical for lymphangioma.  

3) Kawasaki disease  
   - Pros: None relevant here; Kawasaki disease is a systemic vasculitis in children with fever and mucosal changes, not a localized tongue lesion.  
   - Cons: Clinical history lacks fever or systemic symptoms; imaging findings do not correlate with vasculitis.  

4) Malignant melanoma  
   - Pros: Melanoma can appear as pigmented lesions with T1 hyperintensity due to melanin.  
