A) Key findings:
- Young female (18 years) with chronic progressive motor impairment since early childhood (starting around 1.5 years old) with fluctuating course.
- MRI brain: symmetrical T2/FLAIR hyperintensities in supratentorial white matter (excluding U-fibers), splenium of the corpus callosum, posterior limb of internal capsule, pons along trigeminal pathways, inferior cerebellar peduncles, and pyramidal tracts of medulla oblongata.
- DWI: restricted diffusion with low ADC.
- No contrast enhancement.
- MR spectroscopy: lactate peak in abnormal white matter.
- Spinal MRI: longitudinal signal abnormalities predominantly in dorsal columns and lateral corticospinal tracts along the entire cord.
- Clinical features: spastic tetraparesis predominating legs, hypotrophic limbs, increased tone, reflexes, positive Trömner signs, no cognitive impairment, esophoria, weak facial muscles, joint hypermobility.
- Chronic progressive disease, metabolic leukodystrophy suspected, genetic confirmation available.

B) Candidate pass/fail:
1) Hypomyelination with brainstem and spinal cord involvement (HBSL)
   Pros: Involves brainstem and spinal cord; leukodystrophy with white matter involvement.
   Cons: Usually presents with hypomyelination patterns; involvement of pyramidal tracts and cerebral white matter less typical; lactate peak less common.

2) Leukoencephalopathy with brainstem and spinal cord involvement and lactate elevation (LBSL)
   Pros: Exactly matches acronym and clinical/imaging pattern: symmetrical white matter T2/FLAIR hyperintensities including pyramidal tracts, brainstem and spinal cord involvement; lactate peak on spectroscopy; motor impairment; onset in early childhood after possibly viral illness; longitudinal spinal cord involvement predominating dorsal columns and corticospinal tracts.
   Cons: None apparent; fits clinical and imaging findings perfectly.

3) Krabbe disease
   Pros: Early childhood onset, demyelinating disease, brainstem and spinal cord involvement.
   Cons: Usually includes globoid cell leukodystrophy, characteristic MRI findings (frontal white matter, corticospinal tracts, cerebellum), but lactate peak less typical; clinical course more rapid; usually includes peripheral neuropathy.

4) X-linked adrenoleukodystrophy
   Pros: White matter involvement.
   Cons: Typically shows contrast enhancement; clinical presentation usually younger boys; involves more frontal areas; no spinal cord or brainstem predilection as described; lactate peak uncommon.

5) Metachromatic leukodystrophy
   Pros: Leukodystrophy with white matter involvement.
   Cons: Usually no brainstem and spinal cord involvement early; no lactate peak; clinical presentation more global cognitive decline often present.

6) Alexander disease
   Pros: Involves frontal white matter and brainstem.
   Cons: Typically shows contrast enhancement, abnormal astrocytes; no lactate peak; spinal cord involvement rare.

C) Ranking:
1) Leukoencephalopathy with brainstem and spinal cord involvement and lactate elevation (LBSL) - matches clinical onset, imaging distribution (pyramidal tracts, brainstem, spinal cord), lactate peak, and metabolic leukodystrophy confirmed genetically.
2) Hypomyelination with brainstem and spinal cord involvement (HBSL) - similar involvement but lactate peak less typical; hypomyelination patterns less evident.
3) Krabbe disease - less consistent with lactate peak and pattern.
4) Metachromatic leukodystrophy - less brainstem/spinal cord involvement.
5) Alexander disease - less consistent imaging features.
6) X-linked adrenoleukodystrophy - different epidemiology and imaging pattern.

