A) Key findings:
- Patient: 78-year-old female with a long-standing (20 years) painless posterior knee swelling, recent pain after trauma, weight loss, loss of appetite.
- Physical exam: firm, lobulated swelling, no skin changes.
- Imaging:
  - X-ray: soft tissue lesion posterior knee.
  - Ultrasound: large lobulated irregularly shaped heterogeneously hypoechoic mass with internal vascularity, central necrosis/cystic areas, displacing popliteal vessels superficially.
  - MRI: large lobulated T1 heterointense mass with patchy T1 hyperintense areas, T2 heterointense signal, patchy diffusion restriction, heterogeneous enhancement, near-complete encasement of popliteal neurovascular bundle, no skin infiltration.

B) Candidate pass/fail:

1) Clear cell sarcoma
   - Pros: Occurs in lower extremities, especially around tendons/aponeuroses; can show melanin (T1 hyperintensity) patchy areas; lobulated mass; common in younger adults but can occur in older.
   - Cons: Usually arises near aponeuroses in foot/knee; no mention of melanocytic differentiation explicitly; more typical in adolescents/young adults.

2) Malignant melanoma
   - Pros: Rare primary soft tissue melanoma can occur, melanin causing T1 hyperintensity; patchy enhancement; usually aggressive; weight loss.
   - Cons: Primary soft tissue melanoma is extremely rare; more likely metastasis; no skin changes/infiltration; older age; no known primary lesion; lesion long-standing (20 years) less typical.

3) Clear cell soft tissue sarcoma with melanocytic differentiation
   - Pros: Clear cell sarcoma is known also as melanoma of soft parts; clear cell sarcoma typically shows melanin (T1 hyperintensity); lobulated mass; adjacent to tendons/muscles; commonly occurs around the knee; shows internal necrosis, vascularity; encases neurovascular structures.
   - Cons: Age somewhat older; however, can occur.

4) Pigment villonodular synovitis with malignant transformation
   - Pros: Location in popliteal fossa fits PVNS; can present as lobulated mass.
   - Cons: PVNS usually occurs in younger patients; malignant transformation very rare; PVNS often shows low to intermediate T1/T2 with hemosiderin (blooming on GRE); this lesion has patchy T1 hyperintense areas (melanin) not typical for PVNS; no mention of blooming or synovial involvement explicitly; internal necrosis and neurovascular encasement less typical.

5) Synovial sarcoma
   - Pros: Occurs in periarticular regions; lobulated mass; heterogeneous signal; may show hemorrhage or necrosis; can encase neurovascular bundle.
   - Cons: Usually T2 hyperintense; may show calcifications; no melanin (no T1 hyperintensity typical). No mention of typical features like triple signal intensity.

6) Alveolar soft part sarcoma
   - Pros: Slow-growing mass; can show hemorrhage; can be in lower extremities; may encase neurovascular structures.
   - Cons: Rare; typically T1 iso to hypointense; no melanin; age older; no mention of characteristic features.

7) Malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumour (MPNST)
   - Pros: Can encase neurovascular bundle; located along nerves (popliteal fossa); can have heterogeneous enhancement and necrosis.
   - Cons: No melanin; no T1 hyperintensity; no hemorrhage typical; no mention of nerve origin; less likely without neurogenic features.

C) Ranking:
1) Clear cell soft tissue sarcoma with melanocytic differentiation (aka clear cell sarcoma): Fits location, age, T1 hyperintensity (melanin), lobulated mass, vascularity, neurovascular encasement, slow growing with recent symptoms.
2) Clear cell sarcoma: Essentially same entity as above but listed separately; our chosen label is the third option.
3) Synovial sarcoma: Possible but lacks melanin signal.
4) Malignant melanoma: Less likely primary soft tissue, no skin lesion.
5) MPNST: less likely due to melanin signal.
6) Pigment villonodular synovitis with malignant transformation: Rare, but less supportive findings.
7) Alveolar soft part sarcoma: Less likely given imaging and history.

