6) Neoplasm (osteochondroma):  
   - Pros: Patella can have exostosis.  
   - Cons: Imaging shows erosion, sclerosis, and edema with diffusion restriction—not typical for benign osteochondroma.  
7) Neoplasm (chondroblastoma):  
   - Pros: Occurs in epiphysis of long bones, young adult, MRI signal characteristics.  
   - Cons: Usually no sclerosis or erosion on radiographs, no significant synovial enhancement or effusion, no infection signs.  

C) Ranking with tie-breaks:  
1) Fungal osteomyelitis of the patella (best matches infection findings, risk factor of steroids, MRI edema, diffusion restriction, synovial enhancement).  
2) Post-traumatic bone contusion/fracture (less likely due to no trauma/failure on radiograph).  
3) Inflammatory arthritis (less likely due to infection signs).  
4) Neoplasm (chondroblastoma) (possible but less likely with infection features).  
5) Post-traumatic osteochondral defect (less likely without trauma).  
6) Tendon/ligament injury (no tendon involvement).  
7) Neoplasm (osteochondroma) (least likely given findings).  

</analysis>  
<final> Fungal osteomyelitis of the patella </final>
