B) Candidate pass/fail:  
1) Dysgerminoma  
- Pros: Young women; large solid ovarian mass; homogeneous intermediate T2; avid enhancement; high cellularity on DWI.  
- Cons: Typically no necrotic or cystic areas (this tumour usually homogeneous); no mention of fibrous septa or lobular architecture.  

2) Yolk sac tumour  
- Pros: Young women; large solid mass; heterogeneous enhancement and necrosis; high cellularity on DWI; often aggressive and large at presentation.  
- Cons: Typically has elevated AFP (not mentioned); no macroscopic fat; no lymphadenopathy (consistent).  

3) Juvenile granulosa cell tumour  
- Pros: Occurs in younger women; ovarian mass; sometimes hemorrhagic/cystic areas; moderate vascularity.  
- Cons: Usually unilateral large mass; necrosis less common; typically shows estrogenic symptoms (not mentioned); may have more cystic components.  

4) Mixed malignant ovarian germ cell tumour  
- Pros: Young women; large solid mass with heterogeneous enhancement; necrotic areas are common; high cellularity.  
- Cons: Mixed histology can be variable; no specific distinguishing imaging features but fits clinical context.  

5) SertoliâLeydig cell tumour  
- Pros: Sex cordâstromal tumour, can occur in young women; solid ovarian mass.  
- Cons: Usually smaller, more well-defined, less necrosis; less often large heterogeneous masses; less likely to be 17 cm with necrosis.  

6) Immature teratoma  
- Pros: Young women; ovarian mass; can be large; solid and cystic components.  
- Cons: Typically contains fat, sebaceous material, calcifications (absent here); no macroscopic fat or calcifications seen, which argues against teratoma.  

C) Ranking:  
1) Mixed malignant ovarian germ cell tumour – best fits large, heterogeneous, necrotic mass with high cellularity in young woman.  
2) Yolk sac tumour – similar but yolk sac is a germ cell tumour; however, mixed germ cell tumour is broader and includes yolk sac elements.  
3) Dysgerminoma – fits age and solid mass but lacks necrosis/cystic areas here.  
4) Juvenile granulosa cell tumour – plausible but less necrosis/heterogeneity.  
5) SertoliâLeydig cell tumour – less likely due to size and necrosis.  
6) Immature teratoma – excluded due to lack of fat or calcification.  

Tie between 1 & 2: Mixed malignant ovarian germ cell tumour covers yolk sac tumour and other germ cell components; broadest diagnosis explaining imaging findings.  

</analysis>  
