2) B-cell ALL (supported by age, lymphadenopathy, marrow infiltration, soft tissue mass, high FDG uptake).  
3) Osteosarcoma (fits aggressive lesion but age less typical, lymphadenopathy uncommon).  
4) Osteomyelitis (inflammatory signs but imaging more aggressive with soft tissue mass and lymphadenopathy less typical for infection alone).  
5) Langerhans cell histiocytosis (less aggressive imaging, no soft tissue mass/lymphadenopathy).  
6) Occult fracture (least likely).  

Considering high FDG uptake in bone and lymph nodes, aggressive mixed lesion, soft tissue mass with heterogeneous enhancement, and pathological fracture with periosteal reaction in a child, and the lymphadenopathy, the most likely diagnosis is Ewing sarcoma.  
