19133,"Clinical History: A 45-year-old man presented to the Emergency Department with a 4-day history of right iliac fossa pain. He denied fever, nausea, or vomiting. Physical examination revealed rebound tenderness. Laboratory tests showed elevated C-reactive protein (19.6 mg/L) with a normal white-cell count. Two months earlier, he had undergone a laparoscopic appendectomy.
 Imaging Findings: Ultrasound (Figure 1) revealed a blind-ending, aperistaltic, non-compressible tubular structure (luminal diameter ≈ 10 mm) arising from the caecum at the appendectomy bed. The wall was thickened with surrounding echogenic fat. A minimal amount of free fluid was also observed.
 
 In contrast-enhanced computer tomography (CT), multiplanar reformats demonstrated an enhancing tubular remnant arising from the caecum, capped by two metallic clips at its distal end (Figures 2a, 2b, and 3). The stump showed concentric mural thickening, pericaecal fat stranding, and a trace of free fluid. No evidence of abscess or pneumoperitoneum was identified.","Clinical History: A 45-year-old man presented to the Emergency Department with a 4-day history of right iliac fossa pain. He denied fever, nausea, or vomiting. Physical examination revealed rebound tenderness. Laboratory tests showed elevated C-reactive protein (19.6 mg/L) with a normal white-cell count. Two months earlier, he had undergone a laparoscopic appendectomy.
