 Imaging Findings: Ultrasound (US) shows multiple thick-walled collections with echogenic fluid content occupying the left renal fossa and loss of renal parenchyma’s architecture with no corticomedullary differentiation. The thin remaining peripheric parenchymal bundle shows no limits with the thick-walled collections. There is a central pyelic stone measuring 20 mm with a posterior acoustic shadow and a hyperechoic aspect of the perirenal fat. CT (computed tomography) shows left renal enlargement with destruction of parenchymal architecture and dilated calyces consistent with the “bear paw sign,” coexisting blurring of perirenal fat, psoas muscle enlargement and abscess formation, as well as nephroureterolithiasis. The left kidney was nonfunctional at the excretory phase scan. On renal scintigraphy, DTPA injection demonstrates reduced relative renal function on the left (17.7% left and 82.3% right), with pyelocaliceal stasis at the excretory phase. Reduced cortical uptake, particularly in the left upper pole, was seen both at DMSA and DTPA scans.","Renal fossa tumour, Xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis (diffuse form), Pyonephrosis, Hydronephrosis, Urogenital tuberculosis",Xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis (diffuse form),NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>  
A) Key findings:  
