- Both cases involve young patients with port-wine stain on the right side of the face.
- Both show ipsilateral (right-sided) brain findings: cortical/subcortical gyriform calcifications with âtram-trackâ or curvilinear pattern.
- Both have pial angiomas enhancing on post-contrast imaging.
- Enlargement and enhancement of ipsilateral choroid plexus and choroidal angioma in the eye.
- Neurologic symptoms: seizures, developmental delay in the child; epilepsy, progressive hemiplegia, cognitive decline, migraine-like headaches, and ophthalmologic signs (glaucoma, visual field defects) in the adult.
- Imaging shows cortical atrophy, volume loss, ex vacuo ventricular dilatation.
- MR susceptibility-weighted imaging shows blooming representing calcifications.

B) Candidate pass/fail:

1) Meningioangiomatosis
- Pros: Can cause cortical calcifications and seizures.
- Cons: Typically focal leptomeningeal and cortical proliferation, usually no port-wine stains, no choroidal angiomas, no ipsilateral choroid plexus enlargement, no typical pial angiomas; rarely associated with skin vascular malformations; not expected to present with choroidal angiomas or typical leptomeningeal enhancement pattern.

2) Blue rubber bleb nevus syndrome
- Pros: Vascular malformations can involve brain.
- Cons: No port-wine stains, no leptomeningeal angiomas or choroidal angiomas; main features are venous malformations of skin and gastrointestinal tract; brain involvement is rare and not typical; no cortical calcifications or choroid plexus enlargement typical.

3) Wyburn-Mason syndrome
- Pros: Leptomeningeal and cerebral angiomas, arteriovenous malformations.
- Cons: Usually involves basal ganglia, midbrain, thence other deep structures, not cortex with gyriform calcifications; no port-wine stains; choroidal angiomas not typical; no leptomeningeal enhancement with cortical atrophy pattern; typically seen as high-flow AVMs, not pial angiomas with gyriform calcifications.

4) SturgeâWeber syndrome, type 1
- Pros: Classic triad includes facial port-wine stain, leptomeningeal (pial) angiomas causing cortical calcifications (tram-track or gyriform), ipsilateral choroid plexus and choroidal angiomas, seizures, developmental delay, cortical atrophy and volume loss; typical unilateral distribution (usually right side in these cases); matches all imaging and clinical features.
- Cons: None; best fit.

5) PHACE syndrome
- Pros: Vascular anomalies and hemangiomas.
- Cons: Includes posterior fossa brain abnormalities, arterial anomalies, cardiovascular defects, eye and sternal defects; does not involve leptomeningeal angiomas or gyriform cortical calcifications; no port-wine stain typically; choroidal angioma not typical.

C) Ranking:
1) SturgeâWeber syndrome, type 1 - matches all clinical and imaging findings exactly (port-wine stain, leptomeningeal angiomas causing gyriform calcifications, choroidal and choroid plexus angiomas, seizures, unilateral hemispheric findings).
2) Wyburn-Mason syndrome - shares vascular malformation but lacks typical features (port-wine stain, cortical calcifications, choroidal angioma).
3) Meningioangiomatosis - cortical calcifications and seizures but no vascular malformations or port-wine stain.
4) PHACE syndrome - vascular malformations but not matching leptomeningeal or cortical findings.
5) Blue rubber bleb nevus syndrome - no brain involvement or port-wine stain typical.

Conclusion: SturgeâWeber syndrome, type 1 best matches the findings.

