19164,"Clinical History: Case 1
 
 : A 9-year-old girl presented to the otorhinolaryngology (ENT) department with profound hearing loss. On evaluation, she was detected to have right-sided sensorineural hearing loss (SNHL).
 
 Case 2
 
 : A 6-year-old boy was referred from the ENT department with a clinical diagnosis of severe right-sided SNHL.
 
 Case 3
 
 : A 2-year-old child was referred with a clinical diagnosis of right-sided SNHL for MRI.
 Imaging Findings: MRI brain were performed, and the most relevant findings for each case are noted below:
 
 Case 1
 
 : Thinned-out cochlear division of the right vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII) (Figure 1b). Stenosed right internal auditory meatus (IAM) (Figure 1a). The facial nerve CN VII appeared normal.
 
 Case 2
 
 : Non-visualised cochlear division of the right CN VIII (Figure 2a). CN VII appeared normal.
 
 Case 3
 
 : The cochlear nerve is not visualised in the anteroinferior aspect of the right IAM (Figure 3a).","Clinical History: Case 1: A 9-year-old girl presented to the otorhinolaryngology (ENT) department with profound hearing loss. On evaluation, she was detected to have right-sided sensorineural hearing loss (SNHL). Case 2: A 6-year-old boy was referred from the ENT department with a clinical diagnosis of severe right-sided SNHL. Case 3: A 2-year-old child was referred with a clinical diagnosis of right-sided SNHL for MRI.
 
 Imaging Findings: MRI brain were performed, and the most relevant findings for each case are noted below: Case 1: Thinned-out cochlear division of the right vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII). Stenosed right internal auditory meatus (IAM). The facial nerve CN VII appeared normal. Case 2: Non-visualised cochlear division of the right CN VIII. CN VII appeared normal. Case 3: The cochlear nerve is not visualised in the anteroinferior aspect of the right IAM.","Cochlear nerve deficiency, Auditory neuropathy spectrum disorder, Mondini dysplasia, Acoustic neuroma",Cochlear nerve deficiency,NO,"<|channel|>final<|message|><analysis>
A) Key findings:
- All three cases involve children with profound unilateral (right-sided) sensorineural hearing loss (SNHL).
- MRI brain findings specific to each case show abnormalities limited to the right vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII) cochlear division:
  1) Case 1: Thinned-out cochlear division of right CN VIII and stenosed right internal auditory meatus (IAM), facial nerve (VN VII) normal.
  2) Case 2: Non-visualized cochlear division of right CN VIII; facial nerve normal.
  3) Case 3: Cochlear nerve not visualized in anteroinferior aspect of right IAM.
- The involvement is restricted to the cochlear division (auditory nerve) of CN VIII with preserved facial nerve.
- Clinical presentation is profound unilateral SNHL.

B) Candidate pass/fail with 1-2 pros/cons:
1) Cochlear nerve deficiency:
   - Pros: Direct correlation with MRI findings of absent or thinned cochlear nerve. The hallmark of cochlear nerve deficiency (CND) is non-visualization or hypoplasia/aplasia of the cochlear nerve on imaging, often accompanied by stenosis or hypoplasia of the internal auditory canal. This matches the described findings exactly. Clinical presentation of profound unilateral SNHL in children is typical.
   - Cons: None significant; facial nerve normal, which supports CND diagnosis rather than other pathologies.

2) Auditory neuropathy spectrum disorder (ANSD):
   - Pros: Clinical SNHL is present; ANSD can cause SNHL.
   - Cons: ANSD is a functional hearing disorder where the outer hair cells function normally but auditory nerve function is impaired. MRI findings would be normal or nonspecific because the nerve is structurally intact. No mention of nerve hypoplasia/aplasia. Thus, imaging findings of absent or thinned cochlear nerve do not support ANSD alone.

3) Mondini dysplasia:
   - Pros: Mondini dysplasia (cochlear malformation) is associated with congenital SNHL.
   - Cons: No mention of inner ear (cochlear or vestibular) structural malformations or dysplasia on imaging. Findings are limited to nerve abnormality, not cochlear malformation. Therefore, Mondini dysplasia is unlikely based on given imaging.

4) Acoustic neuroma:
   - Pros: Vestibular schwannoma can enlarge IAM and compress CN VIII.
   - Cons: Acoustic neuromas are rare in children; usually present with enhancing mass lesions. No mention of mass lesion, only nerve hypoplasia/aplasia and IAM stenosis. Therefore, acoustic neuroma unlikely.

C) Ranking:
1) Cochlear nerve deficiency - matches MRI findings exactly (absent/scattered nerve with IAM stenosis).
2) Auditory neuropathy spectrum disorder - functional, no structural abnormalities.
3) Mondini dysplasia - no cochlear malformation described.
4) Acoustic neuroma - no mass lesion or enhancement described, unlikely in this age and presentation.

Conclusion: The imaging and clinical findings best fit cochlear nerve deficiency.
</analysis>

